1 magnae et multae: cf. 6, l. 4 magna et gravia, and the note there. Dr Reid in a note on de Amicitia 9, 30 says ‘when two adjectives are in agreement with the same noun Cicero generally connects them with et, where English idiom would osten require them to be put side by side. When multus is one of two adjectives the conjunction is rarely left out, but if multus is one of three adjectives the et sometimes disappears,’ e.g. 6, l. 4.

requiruntur: ‘are needed '; cf. 6, l. 6, and 65, l. 12. For the aliae virtutes see 36,1. 2. Cicero gives a new turn to the argument by showing the special need for a man of Pompey's moral character in the province of Asia.
